# Comprehensive Report on Why People Won't Get Vaccinated Against COVID-19

## Introduction

Vaccine hesitancy, defined as the reluctance or refusal to be vaccinated despite availability, remains a significant barrier to achieving herd immunity against COVID-19 globally. Despite the scientific consensus on vaccine safety and efficacy, a substantial portion of the population remains hesitant or refuses vaccination. This report synthesizes findings from multiple studies and expert analyses to explore the multifaceted reasons behind COVID-19 vaccine hesitancy. It draws on psychographic, sociological, behavioral, and institutional perspectives to provide an in-depth understanding of the drivers of vaccine refusal and delay.

---

## 1. Psychographic and Demographic Factors

### 1.1 Psychographic Influences

Research led by Sarah Bauerle Bass at Temple University highlights that psychographic factors—such as individuals' satisfaction with their health, attention to COVID-19 news, and trust in institutions—play a more critical role than demographics alone in vaccine hesitancy ([Bass, 2021](https://publichealth.temple.edu/news/psychographic-factors-contribute-vaccine-hesitancy-study-finds)).

- Vaccine avoiders tend to be younger (18-29 years), female, Black or African American, and have lower education and income levels.
- They are more likely to ignore COVID-19 news and feel dissatisfied with their health and healthcare access.
- Political affiliation and religion were not significant predictors in this study.

### 1.2 Demographic Correlates

While demographics alone do not fully explain hesitancy, patterns exist:

| Demographic Group          | Vaccine Hesitancy Tendency          |
|---------------------------|-----------------------------------|
| Age 18-29                 | Higher hesitancy                   |
| Black or African American | Higher hesitancy, often "wait and see" rather than outright refusal |
| Lower Education & Income  | Higher hesitancy                   |
| Female                    | Slightly higher hesitancy          |

