## 2. Trust and Institutional Mistrust

### 2.1 Trust as a Core Predictor

A UK study involving over 1,400 adults found that trust in vaccines, government, health institutions, and experts is a key predictor of vaccine willingness ([Mills et al., 2021](https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.01.26.21250246v1)).

- Individuals with high distrust in immunization had only a 10% likelihood of vaccine willingness.
- Those with the highest government distrust had a 25% likelihood.
- High trust in health institutions doubled the likelihood of vaccine willingness.
- Trust in experts was also positively associated with willingness.

### 2.2 Institutional Failures and Historical Mistrust

The University of Michigan study emphasizes that vaccine hesitancy is deeply rooted in institutional mistrust, especially among marginalized communities ([Parthasarathy et al., 2021](https://news.umich.edu/vaccine-hesitancy-rooted-in-institutional-mistrust-could-stand-in-way-of-covid-19-herd-immunity/)).

- Historical abuses such as the Tuskegee Syphilis Study and forced sterilizations have fostered long-standing mistrust.
- Present-day disparities in healthcare access and outcomes reinforce skepticism.
- Government missteps and inconsistent messaging during the pandemic have further eroded trust.
- Media fragmentation and social media echo chambers exacerbate distrust and misinformation spread.

---

## 3. Information Sources and Misinformation

### 3.1 Role of Social Media and Misinformation

The UK study also found that individuals relying on unregulated social media sources (e.g., YouTube) for health information are more likely to be vaccine hesitant ([Mills et al., 2021](https://www.medrxiv.org/content/10.1101/2021.01.26.21250246v1)).

- Exposure to conspiracy theories and misinformation decreases vaccine willingness.
- The "infodemic" phenomenon, characterized by rapid spread of false information, complicates public health messaging.

### 3.2 Limitations of Debunking Misinformation

Larson and Broniatowski (2021) argue that factual corrections alone are insufficient to change minds due to underlying emotional and value-based concerns ([Larson & Broniatowski, 2021](https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/full/10.2105/AJPH.2021.306299)).

- Misinterpretations of scientific metaphors (e.g., mRNA as "software of life") fuel fears of autonomy loss.
- Emotional resonance and values (e.g., personal autonomy) outweigh factual rebuttals.
- Empathy and contextualized communication are essential for effective engagement.

