## 4. Behavioral and Psychological Models of Hesitancy

### 4.1 The 3Cs and 5Cs Models

The World Health Organization (WHO) and researchers have conceptualized vaccine hesitancy through models focusing on:

| Model | Components                          | Description                                                                                  |
|-------|-----------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| 3Cs   | Confidence, Complacency, Convenience | Confidence: Trust in vaccine and system; Complacency: Low perceived risk; Convenience: Accessibility |
| 5Cs   | Confidence, Complacency, Constraints, Calculation, Collective Responsibility | Adds Constraints (barriers), Calculation (information seeking), and Collective Responsibility (protecting others) |

These models help identify targeted interventions based on psychological antecedents ([Razai et al., 2021](https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/01410768211018951); [Betsch et al., 2018](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0208601)).

### 4.2 Four Types of Nonvaccinators

Betsch et al. (2015) categorize nonvaccinators as:

| Type         | Reasoning                                                                                   |
|--------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Complacence  | Do not perceive vaccine-preventable diseases as a threat                                  |
| Convenience  | Find vaccination process inconvenient (time, cost, access)                                |
| Confidence   | Distrust vaccines due to misinformation or ideological beliefs                            |
| Calculation  | Weigh pros and cons extensively, may be confused by conflicting information               |

Tailored approaches addressing each type's concerns are necessary for improving uptake.

